Justin's place is advertised to have 3 BEDS and a sofa bed. The description clearly indicates one bedroom has a queen size bed and the other has a double and single/twin together in the room. And the sofa bed in the living room.  THIS IS NOT ACCURATE.  Instead, what you get is one bedroom w a queen bed as indicated, and one bedroom with a double bed.  Nothing else can fit in that room.  In pre-arrival communication I indicated to Justin that I was having trouble figuring out which bed was in which room based on the pix (i'll explain why in a minute) and just wanted to be sure there were beds for my family because we were expecting the beds as advertised.  So, upon arrival, we find, the queen in a room, the double in the second bedroom AND A TWIN MATTRESS IN A DIRTY RIPPED MATTRESS COVER LEANING AGAINST THE WALL.  That's the third bed, folks, so be warned about that.  There is no way to comfortably and safely even lay it down in that small room, and fit suitcases, etc, and even safely walk in and out of the room. This is SO misleading and is not what we paid for.  I tried to request a partial refund since this is not what we paid for but Justin refused this request. The reason this is even more misleading is that the selection of pictures seems to be intentionally confusing - there are multiple beds pictured on the site - but this turns out to be just the two beds in different linens swapping back and forth in the opposite rooms for the illusion of more beds. Now that I know the layout of the rooms I can identify that there is a pic of each bed in each room.  Regarding the sofa bed and the spare linens provided.. One of the blankets was white with a large round soiled stain on it.  So unwelcoming, unprofessional and just 'not clean' feeling to have soiled blanket left for guest use.  While the location is great and convenient, this place is not worth the money and is not what it was advertised to be for our October stay.  Acknowledgment of the 'confusing' listing and providing a partial refund would have been good customer service and improved our overall impression of Justin and the apartment but that did not happen.

Be aware, however, that this AirBnb is managed by an outside company called StringBnb out of Dallas, and they have their own systems that exist outside of AirBnb‚Ä¶which I thought was a no-no. Emails from them would have helpful recommendations for places to eat, shows to see‚Äîin Dallas, 1500 miles away.
Check-in was the real bummer; one of those Dallas company emails sent incomplete instructions to the uncommon electronic keypads, then hid the detailed check-in info as an attachment at the bottom of the page below the garage opener instructions. So imagine standing on a strange street in Chicago, family members rolling their eyes at me, as I‚Äôm talking to someone in a call center (in Dallas? In Singapore? Not clear.) Pardon the rant, but wasn‚Äôt there a time that Airbnb‚Äôs were real people‚Äôs apartments, not some real estate scheme? Now that‚Äôs not the case necessarily, and Airbnb is not exactly standing up for their original stated principles: real people sharing their real homes in real places at affordable rates. This perfectly fine apartment is set up as if no real person ever stayed overnight. Where are the cabinet drawers for my clothes in the bedrooms? Why was the all-particle- board furniture in the nice-looking dining room only partly assembled? (Fortunately, I had a bike tool that could tighten the loose screws, but the wobbly chairs were a clue that no one ever sat in them before we did.) As is common, silverware was several levels below even Ikea, dishes were a shade above disposable, and a few cups matched, but not all. The floors seemed new, as did the laminate kitchen floor. The bathroom looked like Home Depot‚Äôs finest‚Äîbrand new. There were two coffee machines of different types, with coffee supplied for only one of them. Jarringly, bold silver 72-point signs adorned every door in the place proclaiming NO SMOKING NO VAPING. (I think the point was made at the entrance door; is there a need to repeat it 6 more times?)
Maybe my inner old codger is getting carried away, and I‚Äôm not saying this attractive apartment is not a perfecly serviceable, comfortable place to hang out, but it‚Äôs also an example of the commodification of what was once a clever and joyful idea: the original ‚Äîand now mostly lost‚ÄîAirbnb.
